<TEXT>
truth has been critically wounded 
at the very least by partisan journalism that inflames the bitter 
ethnic rivalries of this patchwork nation 
yugoslavias freewheeling press once the most open of eastern 
europe has become increasingly provincial entangled in local 
conflicts 
the trend is evident in all six yugoslav republics but the 
staterun press and television of serbia seem to lead in the way 
headlines scream hellish police hunt on serbs over accounts 
of routine investigations in croatia an article on federal reforms 
aimed at creating a market economy is introduced with serbian 
economy knifed in back 
accusations flying between communistruled serbia the largest 
republic and the freely elected governments of slovenia and 
croatia have created such animosity that yugoslavia may not 
survive 
serbs and croats the largest ethnic groups in this nation of 24 
million have been rivals since 1918 when the country was born as 
the kingdom of serbs croats and slovenes it was reconstituted as 
a communist republic in 1945 
political and economic differences accentuate the ethnic 
divisions in a power struggle that began with the death in 1980 of 
josip tito who founded the postwar nation and held it together 
croatia and slovenia want yugoslavia to be a loose confederation 
of sovereign states serbia insists on a modern federation with 
power still centralized in belgrade the serbian and federal 
capital 
slobodan milosevic serbias populist leader says he will 
enlarge the republic to take in serbs from other regions if the 
fedration disintegrates 
when croatian police tried to recover hundreds of guns stolen 
from government armories by local serbs banner headlines in serbia 
said croatian police throw serbian infants around and 
fascist terrorists sent to subjugate serbs 
stories below the headlines in the dailies politika and politika 
ekspres did not support the allegations they quoted 
wellinformed sources unnamed and not described echoing 
serbian claims that croatian police recruited fascist 
terrorists to harass the 500000 serbs in croatia 
poison seeps from the pages of politika in all directions 
said croatian writer slavko mihalic everybody is denounced for 
one thing or another and that includes any serbs who dare oppose 
milosevic 
media in slovenia and croatia have accused milosevic repeatedly 
of fomenting ethnic turmoil 
in the croatian parliamewnt deputy stjepan mesic waved a copy 
of politika and declared milosevic is guilty of stirring up the 
trouble in croatia 
belgrade television reported allout civil war between serbs 
and croats in croatia although no one had been killed or seriously 
injured 
to tighten the grip on serbian media milosevic and his 
communist supporters have fired or demoted hundreds of 
independentminded journalists 
after the latest round of 20 demotions the daily vjesnik in 
zagreb capital of croatia accused serbs of pushing their 
hardline concepts to the brink of intercommunal violence to avoid 
holding free elections serbia has scheduled elections for dec 
9 
civil war may be the last refuge for hardline communists 
vjesnik declared 
calls for fairness by opposition parties and independent 
journalists are ignored by serbian television and the 
oncerespected politika 
in june police with clubs broke up a demonstration against 
biased coverage beating several intellectuals and opposition 
leaders 
television did not show what happened and said protesters 
attacked the police a television newscast in croatia that included 
footage of the violence was not broadcast in belgrade 
twothirds of what the belgrade media say is lies said vuk 
draskovic head of the opposition serbian renewal movement which 
threatens to boycott the december elections unless unbiased 
coverage is guaranteed 
serbian television nicknamed milosevision in belgrade 
agreed to carry brief opposition statements it insisted all 39 
registered groups have equal time however even though only three 
have significant followings 
serbian television nicknamed milosevision by residents of 
belgrade carries short campaign speeches by opposition leaders 
only on its third channel seen in just onesixth of the republic 
ante markovic the federal premier is popular with yugoslavs 
generally but not with milosevic who objects to his 
marketoriented economic reforms and attempts to form a national 
political party 
markovic has described in the press as an enemy of the serbian 
people out to plunder our republic 
in an effort to counter such treatment the premier announced a 
weekly federal television program to present fair coverage of 
national issues tv belgrade refused to cooperate effectively 
keeping the onehour program off the air in serbia 
serbian media make their most abusive attacks on the ethnic 
albanian majority in the republics southern province kosovo 
albanians in kosovo have demonstrated regularly against 
milosevics abolition of selfrule in the province and serbian 
police have killed at least 60 in the past 18 months 
the serbian press portrays the demonstrators as terrorists 
who attack security forces with heavy machine guns and mortars 
no serbs have been killed or seriously hurt 
international human rights groups that condemn the repression 
are sworn enemies of the serbs and members of the us congress 
who visited kosovo were mercenaries in the pay of the albanian 
lobby the belgrade papers say 
</TEXT>
