<TEXT>
king fahd is preparing to create a 
royally appointed consultative assembly edging the kingdom toward 
greater democracy in a move clearly speeded by iraqs aug 2 
invasion of kuwait 
the king told newspaper editors in jiddah on thursday that he is 
finalizing plans to set up the body to be known as the shura 
council 
plans to set up the council first were discussed in the early 
1960s successive saudi monarchs repeatedly have delayed its 
consideration partly because of opposition by religious 
conservatives 
the ruling family even built an ornate building for the shura 
council in the heart of riyadh a decade ago it has not been used 
it pleases me that the final touches are being put on the 
shura council and an announcement launching it will be made as soon 
as the final formula is completed fahd said excerpts of his 
statement were distributed by the official saudi press agency 
although fahd did not say so the move to increase consultation 
with the people was at least in part a response to the crisis 
sparked off by the invasion of kuwait 
crises provide the opportunity to do things you havent been 
able to do in the past said judith kipper a middle east expert 
at the brookings institution in washington 
ms kipper pointed to other signs of an opening in saudi arabia 
including the saudis allowing exiled kuwaitis to discuss 
democratic forms of government at a recent conference in the resort 
town of taif 
that shows a kind of recognition of the new realities the 
tide of history the changes in eastern europe the elections in 
algeria tunisia and jordan these are things the people have been 
asking for and for a long time she said 
the demand for greater participation comes mainly from members 
of the often westerneducated middle class who are impatient with a 
system of governance that leaves much in the hands of the royal 
family 
the shura council or majlis alshura is an appointed assembly 
prescribed by the holy book of islam to help rulers manage affairs 
of state it comprises mostly loyalist politicians and scholars 
fahd stressed that the kingdom has always been ruled by the 
tenets of islam that underscore the principle of consultations in 
all matters 
he said that the foundation of the shura council was laid down 
by his warriorstatesman father the late king abdelaziz who 
founded saudi arabia in 1927 
a representative body of local elders advised the royal family 
during the 1930s in the hijaz the countrys red sea province this 
local body gradually ceased to function but the idea resurfaced 
during a power tussle between liberal younger princes and king saud 
in the early 1960s 
when sauds powerbehindthethrone prince faisal formed a new 
government in 1962 he issued a 10point program that included the 
future establishment of a consultative council 
but after he became king faisal took no concrete steps toward 
implementing the proposed majlis alshura 
shortly after faisals assassination in 1975 king khaled 
announced that his government felt bound to complete the 
consultative council project 
but the subject was not broached again in public until 1980 
after the siege of the grand mosque in mecca and shiite riots in 
the oilrich eastern province 
fahd did not mention the proposals after khaleds death in 1982 
leading some analysts to observe that democracy was only discussed 
at times of crisis for the ruling family 
kuwait was the only conservative persian gulf state to boast a 
westernstyle elected parliament that parliament was twice 
dissolved in a decade 
a temporary assembly was elected in kuwait last summer but 
crumbled under the impact of the iraqi invasion 
other gulf states such as oman qatar and the united arab 
emirates have their own shura councils 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

