<DOCNO> AP901109-0009 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
painter rodrigo moynihan hailed by art critics as 
one of the centurys leading portraitists has died he was 80 
moynihan who died tuesday in london painted the future queen 
elizabeth ii in 1946 and prime minister margaret thatcher in 1983 
however art critics say many of his best portraits were of fellow 
painters like francis bacon william coldstream victor pasmore and 
victor willing 
though art critics praised him especially for his portraits his 
work varied widely from abstract expressionism to naturalism 
during his career spanning nearly 60 years 
moynihan was born in santa cruz de tenerife in the spanish 
canary islands off the northwest coast of africa in 1910 
he came to britain in 1918 and was educated at londons 
university college school from 1924 to 1927 he went to high 
school in madison nj he returned to europe in 1928 
early in his career he evolved a form of abstract 
expressionism he began exhibiting with what was known as the 
london group of artists in 1932 and emerged as a leader of another 
coterie called the objective abstractions group 
he later returned to a more naturalistic style and in 1937 
became associated with coldstream pasmore and claude rogers 
during world war ii moynihan became a government war artist 
his poignant private clark ats auxiliary territorial service 
and the grim indignities he depicted in the medical inspection 
proved enduring images of the period 
in 1956 he moved from painting naturalistic landscapes and 
group portraits to nonfigurative art in another shift he then 
moved into what became known as hardedge abstraction 
his 11footlong painting the teaching staff of the painting 
school royal college of art finished in 1950 was hailed as the 
grandest group portrait of his times it now hangs in londons tate 
gallery 
warm gregarious of stocky build a lover of gossip and a 
voracious reader moynihan was professor of painting at londons 
royal college of art from 1948 to 1957 
from 1963 to 1968 he was joint editor with his second wife anne 
dunn john ashbery and sonia orwell of the magazine art and 
literature published in paris 
his book goya about the spanish painter who died in 1828 
was published in 1951 
in 1931 he married elinor bellingham smith then a fellow 
student at the slade school of art she became a well known painter 
in her own right the marriage ended in divorce and she died in 
1988 the couple had one son 
in 1960 moynihan married his second wife the couple who had a 
son lived in provence in southern france that marriage also ended 
in divorce 
