<TEXT>
forget his lips this time any tax increase 
will come over my dead veto says george bush demonstrating 
anew his knack for antitax phrasemaking 
but is it either good politics or good policy 
bush felt a need to back away from his hardline opposition to 
taxes last spring when he entered budget negotiations with 
congress as policy read my lips was not working 
but as politics the hardline opposition to taxes had worked to 
perfection in 1988 understandably republicans who thought it 
would work as well for them in 1990 were angry and frustrated by 
his retreat 
then came his first public comment on the midterm elections in 
which republicans lost one senate seat and nine in the house 
abruptly and to the astonishment of many fellow republicans bush 
rejoined the antitax ranks 
his timing was puzzling congress is not in session and wont be 
until january no one is going to be rushing into the oval office 
with a tax bill and demanding he sign it 
his declaration sounded more like politics than policy more 
like his statement of where he wanted to be in his 1992 reelection 
campaign 
republicans whod never abandoned the tax gospel did not welcome 
bush back 
whos he kidding asked lyn nofziger white house political 
director under ronald reagan hes got a terrible problem hes 
got to reestablish his credibility because at this moment he has 
none 
flip flop flip was the reaction of a republican operative 
who insisted on ridiculing his president anonymously 
never mind the poll numbers that have dropped but still show 
bush looking strong for a president at midterm a better measure 
of bushs political difficulty is the willingness of republicans to 
speak out unafraid of any potential presidential punishment 
two weeks before tuesdays 1990 elections bush got into a flap 
with edward j rollins the cochairman of the house republican 
campaign committee rollins had written a memo advising gop 
candidates who disagreed with the president on taxes to go their 
own way on the issue 
bush was furious he made it clear he wanted rollins fired 
rollins still has his job and the support of house republicans 
undoubtedly if the president is determined to get rid of 
rollins he can do it but the image of the president of the united 
states having to exert himself to dump a political employee of one 
of his partys campaign committees is hardly a sign of strength 
tuesday was a worrisome day for people who have to ask voters to 
pay more taxes that was why governors were among the hardest hit 
pollster mark mellman said if you look at the candidates who 
were defeated in state after state governors who raised taxes or 
whose party raised taxes were defeated 
