<TEXT>
amid all the administration buildup and 
bluster about going after saddam hussein militarily a question 
lingers do they really mean it 
the question is relevant because a military strike against iraq 
was not what the american people had bargained for when us forces 
were first sent to the region 
president bush said initially these forces were sent on a 
defensive mission to protect saudi arabia later after the 
united nations embargo was implemented bush raised the stakes by 
saying the us goal in the persian gulf was to force iraq out of 
kuwait through a policy of economic denial 
lately however the rhetoric has changed not much is being 
said about defending saudi arabia or starving iraq out of kuwait a 
lot is being said about using force and bush on thursday approved 
a substantial increase in the us troop commitment to ensure an 
adequate offensive military option is available a defensive 
force has been transformed into an offensive option 
bush says hes had it with saddam secretary of state james 
a baker iii has been rattling sabres almost daily there is talk 
of a un security council resolution authorizing the use of force 
in august people gasped when administration officials said 
50000 american troops might be dispatched to the gulf now the 
numbers are well over 200000 and rising 
the administration with the help of its coalition partners 
wants saddam to believe his only alternative to withdrawal from 
kuwait is annihilation 
i would like to see a peaceful solution to this question 
bush said thursday if this movement of force is what convinces 
him so much the better 
as former secretary of state henry kissinger used to say a 
military presence does no good if the enemy thinks its not going 
to be used well the united states used force in grenada in 1983 
in libya in 1986 and in panama in 1989 
do those precedents impress saddam only he knows maybe the 
addition of three armored divisions from germany and one from the 
united states to the existing force in saudi arabia will help him 
make up his mind 
from bushs perspective there are powerful arguments for giving 
the sanctions more time to work there was never the slightest 
intimation by the administration at the outset that the sanctions 
would force saddams hand within 100 days of his invasion of kuwait 
a milestone which will be reached this weekend so whats the 
hurry 
beyond that bush and baker are fully aware of how military 
adventurism wrecked lyndon johnsons presidency a generation ago 
johnson campaigned on a peace platform in 1964 then escalated us 
involvement in vietnam quickly after his inauguration 
as us casualties mounted johnsons mandate disappeared and 
the democratic party has never recovered from that debacle it has 
lost five of the last six presidential elections after winning 
seven of the preceding nine 
the current tolerant public mood toward bushs gulf policy could 
change dramatically if bush goes to war without satisfying the 
american people that peaceful alternatives had been exhausted 
if an armed conflict produces casualties perceived by the public 
as unacceptably high and also sends oil prices shooting through the 
ceiling some analysts believe bush could turn out to be a oneterm 
president 
while assuming a more pugnacious public posture bush and baker 
continue to say their goal is a peaceful solution they hope that 
saddam faced with the spectre of empty shelves in iraqi markets 
and one of the most awesome concentrations of military power ever 
assembled will conclude that his best bet is to cut his losses by 
calling it quits in kuwait 
 
editors note george gedda has covered foreign affairs for the 
associated press since 1968 
