<TEXT>
the navy is considering mothballing its last 
two active battleships vessels whose reputations were tarnished 
two years ago by the uss iowa explosion that killed 47 sailors 
the commander of naval sea systems command told congress of the 
possible action thursday shortly after congressional investigators 
recommended that the navy decommission the uss missouri and the uss 
wisconsin 
i can tell you that it is under discussion said vice adm 
peter m hekman jr 
the wisconsin is in the persian gulf as part of the us 
military buildup there the missouri has been conducting exercises 
off san clemente island in the pacific ocean and also will be sent 
to the persian gulf the pentagon said thursday 
the general accounting office the investigative arm of 
congress said defense secretary dick cheney should mothball the 
last two battleships unless middle east operations convincingly 
demonstrate their unique utility 
the gao said the battleships 16inch guns have a maximum range 
of over 23 miles which limits the vessels ability to provide 
effective surface fire support 
in addition the operating cost of one battleship is 58 million 
a year and the vessels require a crew of about 1500 compared with 
about 360 seamen for an aegis guidance missile cruiser 
during the reagan administrations military buildup in the 
1980s the navy at a cost of 2 billion recommissioned four 
battleships that had been in mothballs since the 1950s 
the uss new jersey one of the four had previously been briefly 
reactivated in the late 1960s and served off vietnam 
the pentagon cited budgetary problems in deciding to 
decommission the new jersey and the uss iowa the latter the site 
of one of the nations worst naval disasters the iowa was taken 
out of service last month and the new jersey will return to 
mothballs in february 
on april 19 1989 an explosion in gun turret no 2 of the iowa 
claimed the lives of 47 seaman including gunners mate clayton 
hartwig whom the navy said probably set off the blast 
in september 1989 the service contended in a report that the 
sailor likely inserted a chemical detonator between bags of powder 
in one of the warships 16inch guns to commit suicide 
but last may a new investigation concluded that the explosion 
may well have been an accident caused by unintentionally ramming 
gunpowder bags too hard and too far into the barrel 
the new findings by scientists at the sandia national 
laboratories in albuquerque nm prompted the navy to reopen the 
investigation and halt the firing of the 16inch guns aboard the 
battleships 
the service rescinded its order on the firings when it sent the 
wisconsin to the persian gulf area in august but only after 
limiting the battleship to use propellant charges that have no top 
layer where the accidental blast could occur 
the house hearing broke no new ground on the iowa blast as gao 
witnesses and officials from sandia repeated the testimony they 
provided congress in may 
the economic stabilization subcommittee of the house banking 
finance and urban affairs committee held the hearing 
the subcommittee is not normally involved with navy matters but 
hartwigs family lives in the district of the panels chairwoman 
rep mary rose oakar dohio members of the family attended the 
hearing 
