<TEXT>
a female platyfish looking for a male in her 
life will always choose a guy with a long sporty tail fin 
according to research published today 
that bias says alexandra l basolo a researcher at the 
university of california santa barbara could have led to the 
evolution of a related fish species called the swordtail 
basolo says she proved female platyfish prefer longfinned 
fellows by sewing fake plastic fins called swords on the 
shortailed platy males 
the females went for the guys with sword fins every time she 
said but just why is still not clear 
it could be as simple as the fact that females have a 
preference for a novel male something new that theyve never seen 
before basolo said in a telephone interview 
whatever the reason such a mating bias by the female can 
dramatically change the appearance of a species over many 
generations said the researcher 
platyfish and swordtails come from an ancestral stock the genus 
known as xiphophorus that is swordless species in the genus all 
live in freshwater streams in central america some are popular 
aquarium pets and are raised commercially 
basolo said some evolutionary process occurred to cause the male 
swordtail to develop the distinctive thornlike projection that 
extends downward from the bottom of the tailfin male platyfish 
though related have no swords 
yet for some reason the female platyfish seems to like guys 
with swords 
no obvious use or advantage has been found for the sword said 
basolo the male swordtails develop the elongated tail only at 
mating age 
basolo said that in earlier research she proved female 
swordtails will usually select the males with the most impressive 
swords 
to test if the female platyfish had the same bias basolo 
selected pairs of male swordless platyfish that were matched in 
size and color then on one male in each pair she surgically 
implanted a plastic sword that resembled the size and color of the 
natural swords on swordtails 
on the other male in the pair she implanted a transparent sword 
matched in size earlier studies had shown that this clear plastic 
sword could not be detected by the female platyfish basolo said 
the transparent sword was used to make certain the test was not 
biased by the surgical procedure or by the effect of the sword on 
the males movements in the water this assured that the only 
obvious difference seen from the female point of view would be the 
prominent colored sword she said 
a threechambered aquarium was used for the test one male was 
placed in each of the two end chambers and a female was placed in 
the center chamber she was able to see both males and could 
choose during the test period the males and females actively 
courted each other even though they were separated by clear 
plastic chamber walls six pairs of males were tested with 9 to 16 
females each and a record was kept of the courting selections the 
females made 
given a choice between one of her own males with a sword and 
one of her own males with no apparent sword the female platyfish 
prefers males with a sword said basolo it supports the 
suggestion that female selection thousands of generations ago 
could have led to development of the swordtail species said the 
researcher 
if females preferentially mated with those males with swords 
then over time the trait would become fixed and all males would 
have it she said 
science which published the study is the journal of the 
american association for the advancement of science 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

