<TEXT>
despite spending billions of dollars 
on air defenses and antitank weapons and plans to double the size 
of its army saudi arabia will still be unable to fend off a 
fullscale iraqi attack alone 
unless saddam husseins formidable military machine is crippled 
in the gulf confrontation that means a sizeable western military 
presence will almost certainly have to remain in the region for 
some time to come 
the saudis have spent an estimated 40 billion on advanced 
weapons systems over the past decade but they were unable to take 
on saddams millionstrong military juggernaut when it crushed 
kuwait in august and appeared to threaten the saudis own desert 
kingdom 
king fahd had little option but to appeal for us and allied 
help to protect a country which contains islams holiest shrines 
despite an outcry by some moslem hardliners 
the crisis has benefited the saudis inasmuch as the threat to 
their oilfields overcame the proisrael lobby in the us congress 
which for years blocked the sale of stateoftheart weaponry to 
riyadh on the grounds it was technically at war with israel 
now the americans have pledged to sell the saudis some 20 
billion worth of sophisticated hardware including f15 cd eagle 
fighters patriot missiles 350 m1a2 abrams tanks and 500 bradley 
fighting vehicles 
but even after delivery of the new arsenal over the next two or 
three years analysts say the saudis will be unable to take on 
saddam alone if hes still around 
the saudi defense plan relied on being able to hold the 
attackers off for long enough to get outside assistance said 
nadav safran a professor of middle east studies at harvard 
university 
when saddams troops marched into kuwait the saudis realized 
that even after two decades of beefing up their defenses they 
still didnt have the capacity to hold him off even for a few 
days said safran who is the author of saudi arabia the 
ceaseless quest for security 
king fahd and his defense minister prince sultan are planning 
to more than double the size of the 65000man regular saudi armed 
forces which is supported by a 56000man national guard 
it is unclear where the recruits will come from saudi arabia 
which is as large as the united states east of the mississippi has 
only about 8 million citizens and has long suffered from a shortage 
of men of military age as in most gulf countries the saudi 
military is a volunteer force and no plans have been announced for 
conscription 
according to the governmentcontrolled press 50000 men have 
volunteered for the kingdoms citizens army since aug 2 the 
volunteers receive one months military training 
in the event of war these hastily trained troops are supposed 
to be integrated into regular army units 
merging the regular armed forces headed by prince sultan with 
the national guard commanded by crown prince abdullah has been 
ruled out for the time being 
fahd reportedly favored such a move a decade ago when he was 
crown prince but he was overruled by other members of the royal 
family wisely according to safran because of the threat to the 
monarchy posed by a large army 
even if they should merge the army and national guard they 
couldnt develop a capacity to defend themselves against challenges 
like that presented by iraq safran said 
so to run the risk of a military coup just for the sake of 
developing an army that couldnt even guard against the main danger 
anyway doesnt make sense 
the saudi air force has 179 combat aircraft to iraqs 500plus 
and 550 battle tanks to saddams 5500 
the new us arms package is a key element in the saudi plan to 
bolster its military but us representative mel levine contends 
that the saudis still couldnt defend themselves no matter how 
goldplated their equipment is 
levine an israel supporter and critic of the proposed arms 
sales argues the administration is using the invasion of kuwait as 
a pretext to overcome the proisrael lobbys influence 
despite the saudi military buildup the kingdom will still have 
to rely on balancing regional powers with money and diplomacy 
rather than on military might 
that is how the saudis have coped with regional threats in the 
past including a rebellion in neighboring yemen backed by the late 
egyptian president gamal abdel nasser in the 1960s and the 
eightyear iraniraq war 
 
editors note martin marris is based in bahrain and has covered 
the middle east for four years 
</TEXT>
