<TEXT>
on second viewing six degrees of separation 
reconfirms its status as the most imaginative play of the year 
john guares scathing savagely funny tale of new york chic 
officially reopened thursday after moving from a small theater in 
lincoln center to the much larger vivian beaumont 
the move makes the play eligible for tony award nominations next 
may they could give the prize right now there probably wont be a 
better new play all season 
guares play which originally opened last june resonates on 
many levels social satire rapidfire farce intellectual 
funhouse tragic pop fable and just plain good story to name a 
few 
the plot based on a reallife incident concerns a young black 
man who claims to be the son of actor sidney poitier and how he 
bamboozles all these rich supposedly sophisticated new yorkers 
along the way guare manages to skewer everything from cats 
to overpriced italian restaurants to race relations the author of 
the house of blue leaves has an ear for the way presentday new 
yorkers talk and think 
and jerry zaks directs in slambang style never allowing the 
play to careen out of control 
the bigger theater hasnt lessened the productions impact what 
has oddly enough is the casting of courtney b vance in the 
pivotal role of paul the young black man who disrupts the lives of 
these upper east side trendies vance is a fine actor but he lacks 
the magnetism that james mcdaniel brought to the role last summer 
mcdaniel who left the show to appear in the television series 
cop rock had a sinuous charm a quality that could be 
ingratiating and unnerving at the same time that appeal is missing 
from vances stiff portrayal of the hustler who makes fools out of 
these members of the upper crust 
the rest of the cast was and still is just about perfect 
stockard channing manages to make the plays bewildered heroine 
both funny and poignant she wants to believe pauls tall tale 
celebrating his imagination while forgetting his lie and john 
cunningham acts and looks picture perfect as the wasp art dealer 
not above a little finagling to make some big bucks 
the large supporting cast is just fine and there are several 
standout cameos peter maloney a mournful parent who doesnt want 
to know what his child is doing evan handler as a vindictive rich 
kid and robert duncan mcneil as the country bumpkin destroyed by 
pauls deceptions 
six degrees of separation is one of those rare plays that 
deserves a second look 
frank rich reviewing the play in fridays new york times said 
he found it as funny and moving and provocative as ever still a 
fresh experience not last seasons calcified hit 
</TEXT>
