<TEXT>
the food and drug administration has approved 
the first medication for the treatment of panic disorder a disease 
that will affect 3 million americans at some point in their 
lifetimes 
the medication is xanax made by the upjohn co and was approved 
in 1981 for the treatment for clinical anxiety and anxiety 
associated with depression 
panic disorder is characterized by repeated panic attacks in 
which a patient is struck by intense fear symptoms of panic 
attacks can include chest pain shortness of breath dizziness 
trembling and sweating nausea and abdominal distress the symptoms 
often mimic a heart attack 
the company announcing the fda action thursday estimated that 
between 1 percent and 2 percent of the population an estimated 3 
million americans will suffer from panic disorder in their 
lifetimes 
for about 60 percent of people with the disorder it will 
disrupt their social and working lives which can lead to secondary 
depression said officials of the company based in kalamazoo mich 
a biochemical malfunctioning in the brain is believed to cause 
panic attacks the company said xanax known generically as 
alprazolam can block the attacks by interacting with several 
different systems in the brain 
upjohn studied alprazolams role in the treatment of the 
disorder in a twophase study that involved more than 1700 patients 
in more than 14 countries the company said 
common side effects included sedation and fatigue and they 
subsided when the dose was reduced or as the medication was 
continued upjohn said however higher doses of xanax may be 
needed for longer periods of time to treat panic disorder the 
company said and this could lead to greater chance for dependence 
upjohn officials said that when the treatment is being 
discontinued gradual dosage reduction under a physicians 
direction is essential to minimize the potential for adverse 
effects 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

