mary robinson a lawyer who had fought to 
legalize divorce and contraception was elected president of 
ireland today 
mrs robinson the first woman elected to the office overtook 
former deputy prime minister and defense minister brian lenihan on 
the second round of counting election officials said 
she finished with 528 percent of the vote said tim sexton who 
supervised the count 
in an interview minutes before the announcement mrs robinson 
noted that it was the anniversary of the opening of the berlin 
wall 
and i think something has crumbled away in this election the 
old preconceptions the old political ways said mrs robinson 
who in the past had battled church and state in campaigns to 
liberalize irish society 
i think the joy and the hope and the sense of moving forward 
in this election is quite tangible she said 
she will be inaugurated dec 3 succeeding patrick hillery who 
must retire after two sevenyear terms in the largely ceremonial 
post 
mrs robinson received 848 percent of the secondpreference 
votes from supporters of austin currie the fine gael party nominee 
who ran third 
in the first round of counting lenihan of the fianna fail party 
had 441 percent of the vote to 389 percent for mrs robinson and 
curries 17 percent 
since no one got a majority in the first round the result 
turned on the second choices marked by curries supporters 
mrs robinson was nominated by the leftist labor party and the 
workers party but she belongs to neither the two parties pulled a 
combined 147 percent of the vote in last years parliamentary 
election she is the first president since 1945 not a member of the 
majority fianna fail party 
it was irelands first contested presidential election in 17 
years 
mrs robinson 46 served 20 years in the irish senate but found 
more success in the courts in pressing her causes of equality for 
women and minorities as an advocate of legalized divorce and 
contraception she was often at odds with much of the country and 
her own roman catholic church 
