<TEXT>
mary robinson is a woman of forceful 
opinions about the rights of women and minorities opinions she 
will be obliged to keep to herself as president of ireland 
that doesnt really worry me she said late in her campaign 
if im elected thats an enormous boost and my views are 
known what i would represent is more space and more pluralism and 
more tolerance just by being elected 
mary robinson is the first woman and the first candidate of the 
left to be president of ireland 
the president is the honorific and symbolic head of state 
said tom garvin lecturer in politics at university college in 
dublin by tradition they are expected to be above politics 
in 1976 when president cearbhall o dalaigh exercised his power 
to refer legislation to the supreme court for review there was 
such an uproar in parliament that he felt compelled to resign 
if mrs robinson decides to challenge the traditional 
constraints placed on irish presidents it wont be the first time 
she has challenged the status quo 
when mrs robinson entered the senate in 1969 she was the first 
roman catholic to represent trinity college a historically 
protestant institution and at age 25 she was irelands youngest 
senator and trinitys youngest professor of law 
born in the county mayo town of ballina mary bourke grew up in 
a country that was deeply conservative and dominated by the roman 
catholic church 
her parents both physicians treated her the same as her four 
brothers nobody ever expressed any surprise that i wanted to be 
a lawyer or to do anything different from the boys she once 
said 
if she wanted something she worked with it and got it 
quietly and without fuss but very purposefully her father dr 
aubrey bourke said on thursday 
she accepted a scholarship to trinity college which her church 
then regarded as offlimits when she married a protestant fellow 
law student nick robinson her disapproving parents refused to 
attend the ceremony 
after winning a firstclass honors degree at trinity then a 
masters in law from harvard she jumped into public life 
she introduced legislation in the senate in 1970 to make 
contraceptives legally available and tried again in 1973 and 1974 
in 1976 she proposed that ireland legalize divorce 
she won court cases to permit women to serve on juries to 
overturn laws criminalizing homosexuality to restore inheritance 
rights for illegitimate children and to give women legislators such 
as herself the same pension rights as their male colleagues 
contraceptives were made available by law to bona fide 
couples in 1979 and to anyone over 18 in 1985 but the ban on 
divorce was upheld in a national referendum in 1986 abortion is 
still illegal 
though she is president of cherish which supports single women 
who decide to carry pregnancies to term she also represented 
students at trinity college who were providing information about 
the availability of abortion in britain 
the denial of information is simply putting a further load on 
women who are going to go anyway she said in a recent interview 
the statistics in england show that the numbers are remaining 
at the same level but they are going later at greater risk i 
think that is very cruel and very inhumane she said 
the decision to run for president mrs robinson has said was 
not entirely her own it was put to a vote around the dinner table 
and approved by her husband her daughter tessa 18 and sons 
william 16 and aubrey 9 
tall slender and a bit reserved mrs robinson began 
campaigning for the largely ceremonial office in may her staff 
estimates that she rolled up 25000 miles crisscrossing the country 
in a bus that relentlessly blared an insipid instrumental version 
of the simon and garfunkel tune mrs robinson 
the candidates intention was to shake up the country and to 
challenge a frontrunner who she said simply offered more of 
the same 
asked what she thought was wrong with her country she said 
irish society isnt sufficiently pluralist for a start 
insufficiently tolerant of difference we havent got it in our 
constitution in our laws or in our ethos 
as president she said she would make the sprawling official 
mansion in dublins phoenix park a forum for contact and discussion 
for all manner of groups 
the hand of friendship would also be extended she said to 
the protestants of northern ireland who reject any thought of 
uniting with the republic she will head 
