<TEXT>
commercial satellite companies are selling 
photographs of the persian gulf that could provide sensitive 
military details about iraqi and us troop deployments in the 
region 
the pentagon has tried to keep secret operational information 
about troops in saudi arabia but has not made any move to block 
satellite companies from selling the commercial film spokesman 
rick oborn said 
oborn said he had not seen any commercial satellite pictures but 
said he would be concerned if they revealed operational 
information he said he knew of no attempts to block the sale of 
the photos 
peter zimmerman a professor of applied sciences at george 
washington university said the pictures made available by 
soyuzkarta a soviet trade organization are among the finest 
unclassified imagery i have ever seen 
a camera focused on an area could probably pick up the placement 
of large vehicles the site of a troop deployment and topographical 
details such as trenches he said individual people would be 
indistinguishable 
the pictures would be very useful for iraqi and us forces 
in the gulf to help determine military information about the other 
side zimmerman said 
but jeffrey richelson author of americas secret eyes in 
space said a skilled photo interpreter is often needed to 
identify objects from satellite pictures 
soyuzkarta is one of three commercial firms that sell satellite 
photographs of the gulf the other two are spot image a 
frenchowned company and landsat a us concern 
spot image says it will sell pictures only to people with 
security clearances to prevent the images from falling into iraqi 
hands landsat says its pictures of the gulf region show only sand 
soyuzkarta says it tries to make sure only legitimate customers buy 
the pictures 
soyuzkartas photographs show items roughly 15 feet in size and 
have the highest resolution among the three companies with 
computer enhancement the images are clearer 
velon minshew of fort worth texas a us distributor for 
soyuzkarta said the company has pictures of saudi arabia kuwait 
and iraq for the months of august and september each frame showing 
an area 5060 square miles sells for 1560 
clark nelson said spot images pictures show a resolution of 
about 30 feet the pictures sell for anywhere from 500 to 3000 
generally the landsat pictures of the gulf region show a lot 
of sand cording to dick mroczynski a company spokesman 
landsats pictures much less clear than those of soyuzkarta and 
spot were designed as a mapping tool and are often used by 
geologists and others trying to determine land formations 
under un sanctions the commercial satellite companies are 
barred from selling pictures to iraq 
minshew refused to say who has purchased soyuzkartas pictures 
but the company will sell to legitimate organizations who agree not 
to transfer the information 
nelson of spot image said his company sells photographs to the 
defense department we are not selling to the iraqis or anybody 
associated with the iraqis he said and only those with proper 
security procedures are allowed to purchase the pictures 
nelson said he knew nothing of a recent report in the washington 
times that said iraq is believed to have obtained satellite 
pictures indirectly from spot image the newspaper cited us 
intelligence sources as its source 
television networks have not made wide use of the satellite 
pictures although cbs 60 minutes program showed a photograph 
purporting to show a uranium mine in iraq an interpreter pointed 
out the images 
spokesmen for cbs abc nbc and cnn said their networks were not 
using other gulf pictures 
john stack the foreign assignment editor at nbc said the 
network has used satellite pictures in the past to show among 
other things the nuclear explosion at chernobyl in the soviet 
union 
electronic images provided by commercial satellites are not 
nearly as sophisticated as the data sent by intelligence 
satellites richelson said 
