<TEXT>
washington p a former cia station chief testified friday to 
a federal grand jury about his involvement in the secret contra 
resupply operation of former white house aide oliver north 
joseph fernandez was subpoenaed by irancontra prosecutors who 
are trying to piece together the precise roles in the affair played 
by ronald reagan george bush and key officials at the cia the 
state department and the pentagon 
reagan and bush have said they didnt know north was overseeing 
a private resupply network during a congressional ban on us 
military aid to the nicaraguan rebels in 1985 and 1986 independent 
counsel lawrence walsh is trying to determine if their denials are 
truthful say sources outside the irancontra prosecutors office 
who are familiar with the fouryear investigation 
mary belcher a spokeswoman for walshs office refused to 
comment on fernandezs appearance or on any aspect of the probe 
tom wilson a lawyer representing the former cia station chief 
also declined to comment 
fernandez was compelled to testify under a court order granting 
him immunity from prosecution in exchange for his testimony the 
former cia station chief in costa rica had faced criminal charges 
of lying and obstruction to hide his involvement with norths 
operation but the bush administration blocked the case from going 
to trial last year 
in 1985 and 1986 fernandez acted as a gobetween for north and 
the contras fighting in southern nicaragua as the head of cia 
operations in costa rica he passed along information to pave the 
way for air drops of weapons and assisted on an airstrip 
construction project in costa rica that was to be part of the north 
network 
fernandez also discussed the airstrip project with elliott 
abrams the assistant secretary of state for interamerican affairs 
who met frequently with north 
fernandezs cia superiors told congress in 1987 that they hadnt 
been aware of all his activities on behalf of north fernandez 
contradicted them telling congressional investigators he kept the 
