<TEXT>
us roman catholic bishops gave qualified 
support to us actions in the middle east but said the united 
states should maintain nonviolent pressure on iraqi president 
saddam hussein 
the bishops position was submitted to secretary of state james 
baker iii in a letter sent wednesday by los angeles archbishop 
roger mahony chairman of the international policy committee of the 
us catholic conference 
in the letter the archbishop cited socalled just war 
criteria outlined in the us bishops pastoral letter on war and 
peace released in may 1983 
the criteria make war a lastresort action taken only after 
exhausting peaceful means and weighing possible losses against the 
values at stake and the probability of success 
a resort to war in violation of these criteria would 
jeopardize many lives raise serious moral questions and undermine 
the international solidarity against iraq mahony wrote 
my concern is that the pressure to use military force may grow 
as the pursuit of nonviolent options almost inevitably become more 
difficult complex and slow the letter said 
the catholic conference composed of 390 bishops earlier said 
it opposed iraqs aug 2 invasion of kuwait and supported united 
nations sanctions 
mahony urged continued cooperation between the united states 
the soviet union arab states and other nations 
