cases is getting hotter as researchers look for ways to apply the 
machines that can speed up medical research and help create 
smart bombs among other uses 
if we can make microprocessors smaller and faster they would 
be very useful for advanced weapons systems pentagon spokeswoman 
jan bodanyi said thursday they will be the ultimate weapons 
system once we get supercomputers down to soupcan size we can 
put them on missiles 
industry analysts warn however that despite the push to create 
supercomputers that can handle more information at one time and at 
mindboggling speeds the real challenges are to harness that 
power to maintain top speeds and to make the systems even smaller 
and cheaper 
there arent many people out there who can afford to pay 25 
million to 30 million for a top of the line supercomputer said 
christopher willard senior industry analyst at san josebased 
dataquest another problem is actually getting and using the full 
power of the highly parallel computers its hard to deliver and 
sustain the full power 
officials at santa clarabased intel have refused to release 
information on the companys new supercomputer before a formal 
announcement at an industry conference in new york on tuesday the 
california institute of technology at pasadena where the 
supercomputer will be installed also has refused to comment 
intel which invented the microprocessor is an industry leader 
in chip design and manufacture its new supercomputer will use 512 
of the companys powerful i860 chips now intels most powerful 
machine uses 128 of those chips 
a parallel system links separate microprocessors to create the 
supercomputer which in intels case would reportedly reach speeds 
of up to 32 gigaflops or 32 billion floatingpoint operations per 
second the customary measure of a computers ability to crunch 
numbers and information 
skeptics including intels competitors ncube of beaverton 
ore and cray research inc of minneapolis wonder if the new 
machine can actually reach that computation speed even for simple 
problems 
no supercomputer can maintain that type of speed said 
charles grasfl marketing analyst for cray which dominates the 
supercomputer market i want to know what it can do wheres the 
breakthrough 
one analyst compared supercomputers to using 10000 rabbits to 
plow a field instead of four horses the rabbits may have more 
total energy but controlling that power is difficult still 
scientists continue to try 
whats fascinating about supercomputers is what people will be 
able to achieve one day said abbie kendall spokeswoman for 
ncube right now were on the edge of technology 
in mid1989 ncube introduced its supercomputer which at 27 
gigaflop was the worlds fastest the company is working on a 
quicker model 
the intel supercomputer will reportedly be used for research 
including study of how to better apply such huge computer brains 
supercomputers still have a long way to go in terms of use for 
the average programmer said dataquests willard the 
application i think will come from not what the systems top 
configuration can do but with what its smaller chunks can 
accomplish 
now the marketplace is limited to universities military 
nasa what they need to do is some supercomputing for more 
mundane uses 
ncube hasnt sold its topoftheline 20 million supercomputer 
yet but kendall said the private company expects to sell one by 
mid1991 
now she said ncube sells smaller parallel systems that can do 
more work faster than regular computers a drug company for 
example gets results in three to four hours about molecule 
configurations for new manufactured drugs instead of the three 
months such a computation took previously 
