<TEXT>
a judge has dismissed part of a washington state 
lawsuit against fashion retailer nordstrom inc but left intact 
the states effort to collect back wages for employees who claim 
they were coerced into working unpaid overtime 
the state department of labor and industries in february found 
that nordstrom had violated state labor laws by failing to pay some 
employees for such things as attending company meetings writing 
customer thank you notes and making deliveries 
nordstrom admitted there were some errors in tracking employee 
time and established a 15 million reserve to pay workers but the 
company denied deliberate violations of wage and hour laws it sued 
labor and industries contending the departments findings denied 
them due process 
the state countersued in april and asked that nordstrom be 
forced to pay damages double the amount of money owed workers that 
amount has not been determined 
acting on a motion by nordstrom to dismiss the departments 
lawsuit king county superior court judge susan agid on thursday 
ruled the state couldnt collect damages or constrain the way 
nordstrom pays its employees in the future 
but agid upheld the departments efforts to collect back pay for 
perhaps hundreds of nordstrom employees in washington state that 
labor and industries contends were coerced to work without pay 
we certainly were pleased with where the judge went with her 
ruling nordstrom spokesman dave marriott said the state was 
seeking pretty broad authority 
jim robart an attorney for nordstrom called agids decision 
a major victory 
we were unable to get everything tossed out today but we were 
able to get threequarters of it he said 
state attorneys indicated they may appeal 
without the ability to seek injunctions labor and industries 
would have the power only to enforce labor laws after the damage 
has been done said paul triesch assistant state attorney 
general the limitation on damages also reduced the leverage the 
department can wield to enforce its findings triesch said 
agids ruling was the latest in a series of decisions stemming 
from various legal actions filed by the state nordstrom and the 
