<TEXT>
wholesale prices in october soared for the 
third consecutive month the government said today as the fear of 
war in the persian gulf kept energy costs rising 
the labor department said its producer price index for finished 
goods one stop short of retail jumped 11 percent last month 
after rising 16 percent in september and 13 percent in august 
the threemonth jolt brought producer price inflation for the 
first 10 months of 1990 to a 7 percent annual rate thats sharply 
higher than the 49 percent rate for all of last year is the worst 
since prices soared 71 percent in 1981 
if wholesale inflation were to continue at the october rate for 
12 consecutive months the annual rate would be 137 percent 
however most economists expect energy inflation to moderate 
soon barring the outbreak of war in the middle east or if saudi 
arabian oil production facilities manage to survive a short war 
relatively intact 
in october as in august and september energy prices led the 
index higher rising 8 percent compared with a 09 percent increase 
for food the worst since january and no net change in the 
prices of all other items 
still it was better than the 138 percent rise in energy costs 
in september and the 95 percent increase a month before that 
as temperatures across much of the north turned chillier fuel 
oil prices rose 15 percent and were 675 percent higher than a year 
earlier natural gas costs however edged down 03 percent 
gasoline prices increased 8 percent bringing the level to 502 
percent higher than a year before 
food prices meanwhile turned significantly higher led by a 
95 percent increase for eggs an 82 percent rise for pork and a 
51 percent advance for beef and veal and turkeys costs also rose 
for vegetables and pasta 
the increases were only partly offset by declines in the prices 
of fresh fruit rice chickens fish dairy products coffee and 
cooking oils 
economists were encouraged by the lack of inflation outside the 
volatile food and energy sectors taking it as a sign that the 
sluggish economy is keeping a lid on price pressures 
the socalled core rate of inflation excluding food and energy 
is considered a better barometer of underlying inflation trends 
the good news is the bad news could have been much worse 
said ron schreibman vice president of the national association of 
wholesalerdistributors the overall report is much higher than 
expected but the good news is that core prices remain unchanged 
the price of passenger cars fell 27 percent other declines 
were recorded for mens and boys clothing floor coverings and 
household flatware 
prices rose 34 percent for newspapers and were also up for 
books sanitary papers womens clothing cosmetics tobacco and 
jewelry 
the various changes left the producer price index for all 
finished goods at 1223 in october that means that a hypothetical 
selection of goods costing 100 in 1982 cost 12230 last month up 
from 11470 a year earlier 
inflation at earlier stages of the production process was also 
up sharply driven by energy prices rose 15 percent for 
intermediate goods and 87 percent for crude goods but excluding 
energy and food prices rose only 04 percent at the intermediate 
level and fell 17 percent at the crude level 
crude petroleum prices jumped 292 percent in october and were 
double the level of a year ago 
an example of the three processing stages would be bread for 
finished flour for intermediate and wheat for crude 
economist samuel kahan of fuji securities inc predicted a 
quarterpoint cut in the federal funds rate the rate banks charge 
each other for overnight loans to 7 percent by early december 
the economy looks like its weakening and i think they want to 
provide the cushion to prevent it from becoming a sliding 
collapse kahan said 
