<TEXT>
depressed business across wall street has 
triggered a round of severe cuts that for the first time is digging 
sharply into the highprofile fields of the booming 1980s and 
leaving many senior executives unemployed 
the reversal of fortune has caused punishing losses and pushed a 
few firms into bankruptcy eliminated tens of thousands of jobs 
dried up key moneymaking areas and deflated the image of wall 
street pros as masters of the universe 
in the last two weeks alone 
merrill lynch amp co fired 50 investment bankers reducing the 
department to 575 from about 700 at the beginning of 1990 the 
nations biggest securities firm has eliminated 2300 jobs this 
year no 2 shearson lehman holdings inc has cut 3000 
first boston corp laid off 45 workers from its 475person 
stock division bringing a weeks firings to about 100 hundreds 
more layoffs are expected there by yearend 
bear stearns amp co let go 10 investment bankers from a staff 
of around 200 prudentialbache securities inc fired 120 of 180 
investment bankers and revered morgan stanley amp co pared 50 
bankers 6 percent of its force other firms are firing 
professionals in small increments 
wall street executives say rumors of further layoffs have 
triggered paranoia that is hurting firms ability to do what 
limited business exists salaries and bonuses are forecast to drop 
sharply unlike earlier cuts senior managers and partners are 
being let go 
everyone is looking behind them to see if the ax is coming at 
his head said joan zimmerman executive vice president with gz 
stephens inc a recruiting firm 
you have an immense morale problem right now she said 
when people are this insecure their ability to go out and 
generate business and concentrate on the business at hand drops 
dramatically 
nationwide more than 45000 securities industry jobs have been 
cut since the october 1987 stock market crash the latest 
reductions focus on highly paid investment bankers who handled the 
large mergers and takeovers of the 1980s but have seen their 
business evaporate 
the value of us mergers and acquisitions in the first 10 
months of 1990 was down 50 percent compared with the same period 
last year according to idd information services a research and 
publishing concern 
idd said 3575 deals valued at 1859 billion were completed 
from january through october vs 4273 valued at 3734 billion in 
the same 1989 period the drop was most severe in deals worth more 
than 50 million where investment firms make the most lucrative 
fees 
crucial fees from underwriting stocks and bonds plummeted to 
15 billion in the first nine months of 1990 down 30 percent from 
a year earlier and the lowest level since 1984 according to 
securities data co 
the lack of mergers and underwriting by us companies is blamed 
on a slow economy declining stock market volume and insecurity 
about the future in large part because of the middle east crisis 
analysts projections on further securities industry layoffs 
range from at least 10000 to as many as 40000 
if 91 turns out to be the way the last couple months have 
been then youll probably see much more said lawrence 
eckenfelder of prudentialbache i would say that 91 would have 
to be the washout year 
several wall street executives said the degree of layoffs was 
exaggerated because financial firms typically pare staffing in the 
fourth quarter to plan for next year cynics say its cheaper to 
pay severance than an annual bonus 
people say the environment is rough and tough and i agree 
bear stearns chairman alan c greenberg said that doesnt mean 
it wont change tomorrow 
all agree that wall street firms are adjusting to reality 
following a period of startling growth employment has been reduced 
to 1985 levels but thats still more than 50 percent higher than 
in 1980 
as profits and revenue at top firms sink managers are assessing 
the productivity of certain business lines witness 
prudentialbaches investment banking purge and cutting back 
spending as much as possible 
some executives said the task is made more difficult by the 
uncertain future if firms scale back too much will they be 
prepared for a possible rebound 
theres a slowdown but ive seen four or five cycles 
before said william e mayer who this week announced his 
resignation as first bostons head of merchant banking this is 
just nastier and a little longer 
beyond that theres going to be an industry and people are 
going to do well in it he said but thats going to take a 
couple years 
</TEXT>
