<TEXT>
usx corp and united steelworkers union 
negotiators gave no hint friday on the fate of a new contract for 
18000 employees as saturdays deadline for reaching an agreement 
approached 
neither the company nor the union would discuss the progress of 
the talks which began oct 15 
i dont know whether well have something over the weekend or 
not said usx spokesman ernie glenn 
failure to strike a deal by saturday would not necessarily be a 
major setback the old contract does not expire until february 
but if the talks drag on the risk of losing customers who fear 
a strike will grow analysts said 
theyve got to settle very very soon to avoid losing a lot of 
business said charles bradford an analyst with ubs securities 
in new york they cant wait until early december the customers 
will put their business elsewhere 
the union wants usx to fall in line with other steel makers who 
restored pay cuts taken by workers during the industrys decline in 
the early 1980s 
the wage concessions made by usx workers average about 130 an 
hour said andrew lefty palm the unions chief negotiator 
greg drahuschak an analyst with butcher amp singer in pittsburgh 
said usx can afford to restore concessions today but could face a 
struggle to pay higher wages if the economy doesnt improve soon 
this business is still highly cyclical he said they have 
tremendous capital costs 
industry steel orders in the past month were about 20 percent 
lower than in the same period of 1989 reflecting high inventories 
a slowdown in construction and some automobile plant closures 
bradford said 
in the third quarter usxs earnings dropped 68 percent from a 
year earlier with gains in the energy segment but a 26 percent 
income drop from the steel division 
most major steel makers earnings have dropped in the past year 
and competitors would eagerly snatch customers from any supplier 
whose ability to produce is interrupted by a strike 
but analysts said they expect no strike at usx this time the 
