dow jones amp co inc said friday it was boosting 
advertising rates for 1991 at the wall street journal the nations 
largest daily newspaper 
at the same time the company confirmed it was closing the 
composing operations at its printing plant in naperville ill and 
transferring the plants responsibilities to a plant in dallas for 
a net reduction of 30 jobs 
the moves come as dow jones begins an austerity program under 
which it has frozen capital spending is trying to hold salary 
spending in 1991 at 1990 levels and is taking other steps to cut 
costs 
two weeks ago dow jones said it was boosting the cover price of 
the journal to 75 cents from 50 cents effective dec 3 and the 
yearly subscription price by 78 percent to 109 
the journal has the largest daily circulation of any us 
newspaper averaging about 185 million in the six months ended 
sept 30 
the companys earnings have fallen this year as the slump on 
wall street and the economy as a whole has shown up in sharply 
reduced advertising spending by financial companies 
the new ad rates which take effect jan 2 1991 include 
increases of 6 percent for national edition advertising and bigger 
increases for regional and overseas editions 
the increase will boost the cost of a fullpage ad in the 
national edition of the journal to 105352 
rates in the eastern midwest western and southwest editions 
will increase 7 percent while regional rates will rise an average 
of 9 percent 
the ad rates will jump 12 percent for the wall street journal 
europe and 10 percent for the asian wall street journal and the 
asian wall street journal weekly 
roger may a spokesman for dow jones said the closing of the 
composing operation at the naperville plant effective in january 
reflects technological improvements that enable the company to cut 
the number of its composing operations to three from four 
nationwide 
he said the closing would mean a cost savings and an improvement 
in operating efficiency but would not adversely affect the quality 
of the newspaper 
he said some of the 40 people employed in the composing 
operation in naperville would be transferred to dallas but that 
the company expected there would be a net reduction of 30 jobs 
in addition to the journal dow jones publishes barrons 
magazine the ottaway group of community newspapers and electronic 
business information services its telerate inc subsidiary 
provides financial information 
