<DOCNO> AP901109-0240 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
president bush on friday vetoed a bill 
intended to block drug companies from reaping windfall profits 
through monopolistic marketing of drugs that treat rare diseases 
the bill applies to orphan drugs used against diseases that 
affect fewer than 200000 people it was designed to foster more 
competition by eliminating the 7year exclusive marketing rights 
granted under current law to companies that develop such drugs 
bush withheld his signature from the bill and in taking no 
action at a time when congress is not in session killed it through 
what is known as a pocket veto 
i have serious concerns about the effect that the bill would 
have upon the incentive of drug companies to develop orphan 
drugs bush said in a statement 
rep henry waxman dcalif chief sponsor of the bill in the 
house said he was really shocked that bush did not sign the 
bill because the white house had never made a fuss previously 
about the legislation 
the white house contends that taking away the exclusivity 
benefit actually would decrease the willingness of firms to come up 
with orphan drugs because of the expense involved in the research 
and development 
the legislation bush vetoed would have amended the 1983 orphan 
drug act that established the 7year marketing monopoly as an 
incentive for companies to develop drugs that dont promise as 
large a profit as drugs that are used against more widely prevalent 
diseases 
i believe we must not endanger the success of this program 
which is due in large measure to the existence of the market 
exclusivity provision in the orphan drug act bush said 
weakening the current 7year period is the basis of the economic 
incentive to attract drug firms to invest in orphan drugs 
critics however complain the current law has resulted in 
excessively high prices for some drugs including those used to 
treat aids and millions of dollars in profits by the drug firms 
bush also objected to changing the current laws provision that 
allows orphan drug status to diseases that affect more than 200000 
people when there is no reasonable expectation that the cost of 
developing the drug will be recovered from sales 
the new legislation would have cut off a drugs orphan drug 
status as soon as the number of people who need the drug exceeded 
200000 
bush said he was extremely concerned that individuals with 
rare disease may suffer because of changes that this bill would 
make in the incentives to develop new drug treatments 
the legislation was supported by aids activists and other 
advocacy groups 
the pharmaceutical manufacturing association opposed the 
legislation but said it was not recommending that bush veto it 
the pma contended the current act was working well to stimulate 
development of drugs that otherwise would not be of interest to 
manufacturers 
only six of the 45 orphan drug approvals since 1983 are for 
populations greater than 50000 many of these drugs would not be 
available without the incentives offered by the orphan drug act 
the organization said in a position paper on the legislation 
there was no immediate comment from the pma on bushs veto said 
spokesman mark grayson 
but waxman alleged some drug companies have gotten to the ear 
of the white house 
waxman said companies dont want to lose the advantage they 
enjoy by being the monopoly supplier of drugs used to treat 
diseases that once were limited to a small population but have 
spread to thousands of people 
he said drugs to treat aids for example should no longer be 
considered orphan drugs 
sen orrin hatch rutah who sponsored the bill in the senate 
was not immediately available for comment 
the food and drug administration has granted socalled orphan 
status to more than 375 drugs more than 40 of which have reached 
the market critics have been concerned that some of these drugs 
were producing monopolistic windfalls for the drug companies that 
marketed them 
some of the diseases that orphan drugs have been developed to 
treat include huntingtons disease tourettes syndrome narcolepsy 
and muscular dystrophy 
on a separate matter bush on friday signed a bill requiring 
food manufacturers to put more nutrition information on the labels 
of food packaging 
the bill also would prohibit manufacturers from making health 
claims on their packaging unless scientifically proven according to 
the food and drug administration 
the legislation mandates that most bulk food in bins raw fish 
and fruits and vegetables be displayed with a sign or brochure 
providing nutritional information 
food labels will have to show calories calories from fat fat 
content saturated fat cholesterol sodium total carbohydrates 
complex carbohydrates sugars dietary fiber and protein 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

