<DOCNO> AP901109-0251 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the government declared the freedom national 
bank of new york insolvent friday closing what local officials 
called the largest minorityowned bank in the country 
the bank had assets of 1019 million its main branch was in 
harlem and two others were in brooklyn 
the federal deposit insurance corp the federal agency that 
closed the bank by law must reimburse depositors with holdings up 
to 100000 each 
however about 100 of the banks accounts exceed the 100000 
limit totaling 11 million those uninsured depositors will share 
with the fdic the proceeds of liquidating the failed banks assets 
the fdic said there were no bids by other banks to take over the 
freedom national bank 
the bank has a total of 22000 accounts in which 908 million 
had been deposited 
debts and liabilities owed by the bank but secured by various 
types of collateral total about 91 million 
in a statement mayor david dinkins expressed regret over the 
banks closing he said it was the largest minorityowned us 
banking company 
since its founding in 1964 freedom has served as the 
financial backbone of the harlem community at a time when few other 
institutions showed much interest in doing business there 
dinkins said in a statement 
over its 26 years it has provided loans and safeguarded the 
deposits of thousands of neighborhood residents and businesses 
dinkins said the city has accounts at the bank that totaled 
300000 sept 30 but that the money is in separate accounts of no 
more than 100000 each and is therefore protected 
deposits up to the 100000 limit will be made available to 
account holders starting tuesday the fdic had not yet determined 
where the reimbursements would be made 
</TEXT>
